mericas and Europe were adapted to meet local exigencies to how socialist-bloc and nonaligned Cold War organizations facilitated the circulation of popular music throughout the region, the contributors outline how music forged and challenged alliances, revolutions, and countercultures. They also show how the Cold War's legacy shapes contemporary culture, particularly in the ways 1990s and 2000s J-pop and K-pop are rooted in American attempts to foster economic exchange in East Asia in the 1960s.Throughout, Sound Alignments demonstrates that the experiences of the Cold War in Asia were as diverse and dynamic as the music heard and performed in it.Contributors. Marié Abe, Michael K. Bourdaghs, Paola Iovene, Nisha Kommattam, Jennifer Lindsay, Kaley Mason, Anna Schultz, Hyunjoon Shin, C. J. W.-L. Wee, Hon-Lun (Helan) Yang, Christine R. Yano, Qian Zhang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCold War. 0aMusicxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aMusicxHistory and criticismzAsia. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszAsia. 0aMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczAsiaxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismzAsia. 0aPopular musicxPolitical aspectszAsia. 0aPopular musiczAsiaxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aAbe, Marié, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdaghs, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdaghs, Michael K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIovene, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIovene, Paola, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKommattam, Nisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindsay, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc